Exercise 1

** Built an arbitrary two-mode network and retrieve the associated one-mode networks, What do the diagonal and off-diagonal entries mean?**

library(igraph)
library(statnet)
set.seed(123)
n1 <- 6
n2 <- 5
n <- n1 + n2
# define the probability of connection among nodes of different sets
p <- .5
# generate random bipartite graph.
g <- sample_bipartite(n1, n2, type="Gnp", p = p, directed=FALSE)
g
## IGRAPH 175fefd U--B 11 13 -- Bipartite Gnp random graph
## + attr: name (g/c), p (g/n), type (v/l)
## + edges from 175fefd:
##  [1] 2-- 7 6-- 7 1-- 8 2-- 8 3-- 8 3-- 9 1--10 2--10 3--10 4--10 6--10
## [12] 5--11 6--11
# check the type attribute:
V(g)$type
##  [1] FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE
AM <- get.incidence(g)
colnames(AM) <- c("M1","M2","M3","M4","M5")
row.names(AM) <- c("F1","F2","F3","F4","F5","F6")
b <- graph.incidence(AM)
AM
##    M1 M2 M3 M4 M5
## F1  0  1  0  1  0
## F2  1  1  0  1  0
## F3  0  1  1  1  0
## F4  0  0  0  1  0
## F5  0  0  0  0  1
## F6  1  0  0  1  1
# define color and shape mappings.
col <- c("blue", "yellow")
shape <- c("circle", "square")

plot(b,
     vertex.color = col[as.numeric(V(b)$type)+1],
     vertex.shape = shape[as.numeric(V(b)$type)+1],layout=layout.bipartite,
     vertex.size=20)

  is_bipartite(g)
## [1] TRUE
#alternative plotting , I just remove layout
plot(b,
  vertex.color = col[as.numeric(V(b)$type)+1],
  vertex.shape = shape[as.numeric(V(b)$type)+1],
  vertex.size=20)

is_bipartite(g)
## [1] TRUE

we project two mode graph to one mode graph

g.pr <- bipartite.projection(b)

g.pr
## $proj1
## IGRAPH d8acbcf UNW- 6 11 -- 
## + attr: name (v/c), weight (e/n)
## + edges from d8acbcf (vertex names):
##  [1] F1--F2 F1--F3 F1--F4 F1--F6 F2--F6 F2--F3 F2--F4 F3--F4 F3--F6 F4--F6
## [11] F5--F6
## 
## $proj2
## IGRAPH bad1c07 UNW- 5 7 -- 
## + attr: name (v/c), weight (e/n)
## + edges from bad1c07 (vertex names):
## [1] M1--M2 M1--M4 M1--M5 M2--M4 M2--M3 M3--M4 M4--M5
g.side1 <-g.pr$proj1
g.side2 <- g.pr$proj2

get.adjacency(g.side1,sparse=FALSE,attr="weight")
##    F1 F2 F3 F4 F5 F6
## F1  0  2  2  1  0  1
## F2  2  0  2  1  0  2
## F3  2  2  0  1  0  1
## F4  1  1  1  0  0  1
## F5  0  0  0  0  0  1
## F6  1  2  1  1  1  0
get.adjacency(g.side2,sparse=FALSE,attr="weight")
##    M1 M2 M3 M4 M5
## M1  0  1  0  2  1
## M2  1  0  1  3  0
## M3  0  1  0  1  0
## M4  2  3  1  0  1
## M5  1  0  0  1  0
#we plot each of the one mode network:
shapes <- c("circle","square")
colors <- c("blue","red")
op <- par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(g.side1,vertex.color="blue",
     vertex.shape="circle",main="side1",
     edge.width=E(g.side1)$weight*2,
     vertex.size=15,vertex.label.degree=-pi/2,
     vertex.label.dist=1.2,vertex.label.cex=1)
plot(g.side2,vertex.color="red",
     vertex.shape="square",main="side2",
     edge.width=E(g.side1)$weight*2,
     vertex.size=15,vertex.label.degree=-pi/2,
     vertex.label.dist=1.2,vertex.label.cex=1)

What do the diagonal and off-diagonal entries mean? The adjacency matrix of each one-mode projection males are undirectly connected through thier shared friend. M1 and M4 are indirectly connected through thier 2 common female friend but M1 and M2 are indirectly connected via one female friend.

Exercise 2

Use the Davis data (Davis.txt file from the first R Lab) and transform it in a hypergraph of an object of class network.

A hypergraph is just a graph G=(V,E) where V is the set of vertices (nodes) and E is a subset of the powerset of V. It is a data structure. So a common graph is just a hypergraph with rank 2. (i.e each set in E contains exactly two vertices). A directed hypergraph uses pairs (X,Y) as the edges where X and Y are sets.
